00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:24.240 align:middle line:84%
So the fundamental
welfare theorems,

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:26.370 align:middle line:90%
there are two of them.

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:27.900 align:middle line:84%
That's going to be
the focus today.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:31.880 align:middle line:90%


00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.250 align:middle line:84%
First one, competitive
equilibria or while raising

00:02:36.250 --> 00:02:37.970 align:middle line:90%
equilibria are Pareto optimal.

00:02:37.970 --> 00:02:41.540 align:middle line:90%


00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:45.600 align:middle line:84%
We've defined both
concepts earlier.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.060 align:middle line:84%
We'll raise the equilibrium
Pareto optimality.

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:51.670 align:middle line:90%
So that's review.

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:53.950 align:middle line:84%
I've mentioned that these
welfare theorems are true,

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:58.030 align:middle line:84%
but we've never gone through
exactly under what conditions

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:01.725 align:middle line:90%
and how the proofs go.

00:03:01.725 --> 00:03:03.100 align:middle line:84%
That's the first
welfare theorem.

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:07.390 align:middle line:84%
The second welfare theorem,
any Pareto-optimal allocation

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:10.480 align:middle line:84%
can be supported as a
competitive equilibrium

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:11.340 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:14.180 align:middle line:90%


00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:16.970 align:middle line:84%
And again, we'll go
through the proofs.

00:03:16.970 --> 00:03:21.440 align:middle line:84%
Actually, two kinds of proofs
of the second welfare theorem.

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:24.215 align:middle line:84%
One, I would say
is constructive.

00:03:24.215 --> 00:03:26.510 align:middle line:84%
It's matching up
first-order conditions.

00:03:26.510 --> 00:03:31.060 align:middle line:84%
And the second one is using
separating hyperplanes

00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:33.820 align:middle line:90%
in convex spaces.

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:38.050 align:middle line:84%
The second is more general
than the first, in the sense

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:43.510 align:middle line:84%
that it applies to
many environments.

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:45.580 align:middle line:84%
But the first
constructive proof is

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.550 align:middle line:90%
providing a lot of intuition.

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:52.510 align:middle line:84%
So in some sense, when
these welfare theorems hold,

00:03:52.510 --> 00:03:56.320 align:middle line:84%
you can go back and forth
between optimal allocations

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:57.900 align:middle line:90%
and competitive allocations.

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:00.970 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:04.540 align:middle line:84%
A particular competitive
equilibrium is Pareto optimal,

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:09.610 align:middle line:84%
but that doesn't mean that you
couldn't contemplate others.

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:12.340 align:middle line:84%
It's associated with a
particular distribution

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:17.260 align:middle line:84%
of wealth from
private ownership.

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:20.140 align:middle line:84%
And if you want to get to
other redistribute wealth

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:23.890 align:middle line:84%
and benefit, some at
the expense of others,

00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:26.680 align:middle line:84%
find another
Pareto-optimal allocation,

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:30.920 align:middle line:84%
there's also a way to support
any additional one like that.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.650 align:middle line:84%
But it is going to require
these kinds of transfers.

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:38.340 align:middle line:84%
So that's the overall
theme for today.

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:42.500 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind you, paste
