00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:10.610 align:middle line:84%
to see, it is nevertheless
present in consumption

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:12.950 align:middle line:90%
as well, with this upsloping.

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:17.810 align:middle line:84%
So in some sense, this
cross-sectional gradient

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:20.810 align:middle line:84%
reflects the lambda
weights, so to speak,

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:23.540 align:middle line:84%
when we solve for the
optimal allocation

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:28.190 align:middle line:84%
of risk sharing in this
village India environment.

00:05:28.190 --> 00:05:31.910 align:middle line:84%
We maximize the lambda
weighted sum of utilities

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:36.380 align:middle line:84%
and intuitively as
well as, in particular,

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:40.730 align:middle line:84%
for particular functional forms,
the higher are the lambdas,

00:05:40.730 --> 00:05:44.880 align:middle line:84%
the higher would be
average consumption.

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:48.480 align:middle line:84%
So that gradient reflects
the lambda, so to speak.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:51.830 align:middle line:84%
Now, we only looked
at Pareto optimality

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:55.070 align:middle line:84%
when we did the optimal
allocation of risk sharing.

00:05:55.070 --> 00:05:57.440 align:middle line:84%
We didn't really link it up
to competitive equilibria,

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:59.720 align:middle line:84%
but we're going
to do that today.

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:03.890 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, we could ask
whether the implicit lambdas

00:06:03.890 --> 00:06:06.830 align:middle line:84%
in that gradient are
related to wealth.

00:06:06.830 --> 00:06:09.500 align:middle line:84%
Think about the village
achieving its allocation

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:13.070 align:middle line:84%
of resources to competitive
markets and, in particular,

00:06:13.070 --> 00:06:14.690 align:middle line:90%
through private ownership.

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:18.800 align:middle line:84%
Then, we should see a
correlation between the lambda

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:22.020 align:middle line:84%
weights and other variables
that represent wealth.

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:25.640 align:middle line:84%
So I don't think I showed
you this slide earlier.

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:29.600 align:middle line:84%
It is in the paper risk and
insurance village India.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:32.090 align:middle line:84%
And here, you can
see a regression

00:06:32.090 --> 00:06:38.530 align:middle line:84%
of that gradient, the lambdas in
particular, that are backed out

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:42.850 align:middle line:84%
from the empirical work, from
