00:06:57.350 --> 00:06:59.170 align:middle line:84%
So that would seem
to suggest there

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:05.140 align:middle line:84%
is some correlation between
wealth and the lambda weights,

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:14.740 align:middle line:84%
although it's not uniform and
not true at all in Shirapur.

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:18.460 align:middle line:84%
So it's mostly apparent in
only one of the three villages,

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:19.870 align:middle line:90%
in Aurepalle.

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:22.330 align:middle line:84%
And what you don't
know from this table

00:07:22.330 --> 00:07:28.600 align:middle line:84%
is that the ownership of
bulls and so on moves around

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:29.630 align:middle line:90%
over time.

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:34.270 align:middle line:84%
So it's not so representative
of wealth anyway.

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So this might suggest that the
allocation in those villages,

00:07:38.770 --> 00:07:42.910 align:middle line:84%
even if achieved through
competitive market forces,

00:07:42.910 --> 00:07:47.350 align:middle line:84%
also includes some
kind of redistribution

00:07:47.350 --> 00:07:50.230 align:middle line:84%
from the upper-caste
landowners to the poor.

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:53.520 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:57.300 align:middle line:84%
So let's turn to the
welfare theorems.

00:07:57.300 --> 00:08:02.760 align:middle line:84%
First one, suppose we had a
competitive allocation, denoted

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:08.190 align:middle line:84%
x star, y star with
price p and wealth w.

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:13.270 align:middle line:84%
And actually, this slide
treats it more generally.

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:16.390 align:middle line:84%
A competitive equilibrium
with transfers.

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:20.380 align:middle line:84%
A special case, of course,
of a competitive equilibrium

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:24.600 align:middle line:84%
would be no transfers and
just private ownership.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:26.560 align:middle line:84%
But let's start with a
competitive equilibrium

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:28.660 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:33.820 align:middle line:84%
And if preferences are rational
and locally nonsatiated,

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:39.750 align:middle line:84%
that allocation x star, y star
is Pareto optimal or, for sure,

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:43.320 align:middle line:84%
competitive equilibrium
or Pareto optimal.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:47.910 align:middle line:90%
Strikingly, you don't need much.

00:08:47.910 --> 00:08:51.810 align:middle line:84%
All you need is essentially
rational preferences

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:55.200 align:middle line:90%
and local nonsatiation.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:58.110 align:middle line:84%
And intuitively, the
reason you need so little

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:00.120 align:middle line:84%
is that we're given
a lot to begin with.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:03.970 align:middle line:84%
We're given the existence
of a competitive equilibrium

00:09:03.970 --> 00:09:05.640 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:10.142 align:middle line:84%
So we don't have to have all the
assumptions that go with that

00:09:10.142 --> 00:09:12.070 align:middle line:90%
that ensure that equilibrium.

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:15.040 align:middle line:84%
That's kind of taken as
a given in the statement

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:17.890 align:middle line:90%
of the problem.

00:09:17.890 --> 00:09:20.590 align:middle line:84%
In particular, we don't have
to talk about the consumption

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:24.130 align:middle line:84%
sets of the agents,
other than they

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:27.010 align:middle line:84%
have to be constructed
in a way that

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:29.530 align:middle line:84%
is consistent with
local nonsatiation.

00:09:29.530 --> 00:09:32.980 align:middle line:84%
We don't have to say anything
about production sets,

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:35.800 align:middle line:84%
other than evidently they're
nonempty because there's

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:42.220 align:middle line:84%
a y star up here, although in
principle, that could be 0.

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:45.430 align:middle line:90%
So very little is assumed.

00:09:45.430 --> 00:09:50.500 align:middle line:84%
So here's an illustration
in the Edgeworth box

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:52.240 align:middle line:90%
of the first welfare theorem.

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:55.420 align:middle line:84%
We start out with the
endowment, private ownership.

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:57.100 align:middle line:90%
No production.

00:09:57.100 --> 00:10:03.390 align:middle line:84%
And we find prices such
that each of the two agents

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:05.970 align:middle line:90%
here are maximizing.

00:10:05.970 --> 00:10:11.550 align:middle line:84%
And along their budget line,
it's the same line for each,

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:12.315 align:middle line:90%
in some sense.

00:10:12.315 --> 00:10:15.540 align:middle line:90%


00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:18.090 align:middle line:84%
Household 1 giving up
Good 1, getting Good 2.

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:21.150 align:middle line:84%
Household 2 going in
the opposite direction,

00:10:21.150 --> 00:10:24.060 align:middle line:84%
giving up Good 2
and getting Good 1.

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:26.050 align:middle line:90%
And here's the equilibrium.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:28.650 align:middle line:84%
And you can see
how beautiful it is

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:30.780 align:middle line:84%
because the marginal
rates of substitution

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:33.720 align:middle line:90%
match up with the price ratio.

00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:37.330 align:middle line:84%
And we've achieved the
competitive equilibrium.

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:39.810 align:middle line:84%
So competitive equilibrium
is Pareto optimal.

00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:42.130 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it's
not the only one.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:46.500 align:middle line:84%
There are many, many
others, as you can see.

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:47.970 align:middle line:84%
But the first
welfare theorem just

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:52.980 align:middle line:84%
starts with a particular
competitive equilibrium,

00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:55.200 align:middle line:90%
in this case, private ownership.

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.315 align:middle line:84%
Now, how do we
prove the theorem?

00:10:57.315 --> 00:11:00.460 align:middle line:90%


00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:03.220 align:middle line:84%
The picture makes
it seem obvious.

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:05.515 align:middle line:84%
But we want the proof
to be more general.

00:11:05.515 --> 00:11:08.530 align:middle line:90%


00:11:08.530 --> 00:11:13.560 align:middle line:84%
So if preferences are
locally nonsatiated, then,

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:19.310 align:middle line:84%
in particular, if the Xi star
of the competitive equilibria

00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:25.950 align:middle line:84%
is maximizing under
Agent I's preferences,

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:29.610 align:middle line:84%
maximizing in the sense that
it's the utility maximizing

00:11:29.610 --> 00:11:34.770 align:middle line:84%
object in h and i's budget set,
this is expenditures less than

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:41.340 align:middle line:84%
or equal to wealth, then for
any other point Xi, which

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:48.820 align:middle line:84%
is at least as good in
the preference as Xi star,

00:11:48.820 --> 00:11:51.790 align:middle line:84%
it must be the case
that the valuation

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:56.680 align:middle line:84%
of that other allocation,
evaluated price's p,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.770 align:middle line:84%
is not less than,
is greater than

00:11:59.770 --> 00:12:03.940 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the
valuation of expenditures

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:06.430 align:middle line:90%
at the competitive equilibrium.

00:12:06.430 --> 00:12:08.170 align:middle line:90%
That's kind a lot to take in.

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:11.680 align:middle line:84%
The key part of it
is this implication,

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:13.960 align:middle line:84%
and I used to have the
proof all written out.

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:16.240 align:middle line:84%
But it takes like
six or seven lines.

00:12:16.240 --> 00:12:18.010 align:middle line:84%
Let me just give
you the intuition.

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:20.260 align:middle line:90%
Suppose it weren't true?

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:27.830 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that if pxi were
strictly less than pxi star.

00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:31.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, they're spending
everything they have.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:35.570 align:middle line:84%
So pxi star is their
wealth, and they could

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:38.480 align:middle line:90%
spend less if they chose to.

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:41.840 align:middle line:84%
If pxi were less
than pxi star, that

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:45.810 align:middle line:84%
would be a point where
they're spending less.

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:50.060 align:middle line:84%
However, finally, we come
back to the nonsatiation.

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:54.350 align:middle line:84%
Draw a little ball
or circle around Xi.

00:12:54.350 --> 00:12:56.160 align:middle line:84%
If you remember the
statement, there

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:58.410 align:middle line:84%
has to be a bundle
that's strictly preferred

00:12:58.410 --> 00:13:01.230 align:middle line:90%
to Xi that's close by.

00:13:01.230 --> 00:13:07.450 align:middle line:84%
Since it's close by, it is also
spending less than Xi star.

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:10.410 align:middle line:84%
So now, there's
a preferred point

00:13:10.410 --> 00:13:14.700 align:middle line:84%
because Xi is at least
as good as Xi star.

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:19.170 align:middle line:84%
This other point is going to
strictly dominate Xi and hence

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:22.240 align:middle line:84%
dominate in the
preference at Xi star.

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:25.560 align:middle line:84%
So there's a point in the
carrier of the budget set

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:29.040 align:middle line:84%
which is strictly preferred
to the chosen point Xi

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:33.360 align:middle line:84%
star, which contradicts
utility maximization.

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:35.130 align:middle line:84%
Even took me quite
a while to say

00:13:35.130 --> 00:13:38.400 align:middle line:84%
it, but it's quite intuitive
when you think about it.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:41.220 align:middle line:90%


00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:44.010 align:middle line:84%
So this innocuous
little Lemma is

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:49.050 align:middle line:84%
about to get used with the proof
of the first welfare theorem,

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:55.150 align:middle line:84%
namely that a competitive
equilibrium is Pareto optimal.

00:13:55.150 --> 00:13:56.980 align:middle line:90%
Proof by contradiction.

00:13:56.980 --> 00:13:58.285 align:middle line:90%
No, it's not.

00:13:58.285 --> 00:13:59.800 align:middle line:90%
You say it is.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:03.440 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to assume
it's not Pareto optimal.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:06.480 align:middle line:84%
Well, any point that's
not Pareto optimal means,

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:09.440 align:middle line:84%
of course, you
guys all remember,

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:12.770 align:middle line:84%
that there's a feasible
allocation, which

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:15.050 align:middle line:84%
has the property
that it's at least as

00:14:15.050 --> 00:14:20.150 align:middle line:84%
good as the star competitive
allocation for all i

00:14:20.150 --> 00:14:25.700 align:middle line:84%
and strictly dominates for at
least one agent, in this case,

00:14:25.700 --> 00:14:26.885 align:middle line:90%
denoted i prime.

00:14:26.885 --> 00:14:29.670 align:middle line:90%


00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:33.720 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we mean by Xi
star not being Pareto optimal.

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:43.540 align:middle line:84%
Now, clearly, for
the guys, Xi prime,

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:46.330 align:middle line:84%
these bundles are strictly
preferred to the one chosen.

00:14:46.330 --> 00:14:48.880 align:middle line:84%
So they cannot be
in the budget set.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:53.090 align:middle line:84%
So we have a strict
inequality in expenditures

00:14:53.090 --> 00:14:54.515 align:middle line:90%
for those i prime guys.

00:14:54.515 --> 00:14:57.460 align:middle line:90%


00:14:57.460 --> 00:15:00.550 align:middle line:84%
But what about these guys that
were only weakly indifferent?

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:01.940 align:middle line:90%
That could be a problem.

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:04.210 align:middle line:90%
But no, we've got it covered.

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.040 align:middle line:84%
By the previous
Lemma, we already

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:11.460 align:middle line:84%
know that expenditures
are not less.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:16.050 align:middle line:84%
So we have strictly
greater, weakly greater

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:22.020 align:middle line:84%
expenditures of the alternative
supposed dominating allocation

00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:26.010 align:middle line:84%
with the given
competitive allocation.

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:29.670 align:middle line:84%
Let's sum up the values
over all the households

00:15:29.670 --> 00:15:33.270 align:middle line:84%
I, and we're going to
get a strict inequality.

00:15:33.270 --> 00:15:36.260 align:middle line:84%
So if it were true that there
exists an allocation, which

00:15:36.260 --> 00:15:39.200 align:middle line:84%
Pareto dominates the
competitive equilibrium,

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:42.560 align:middle line:84%
it would be associated
at the equilibrium prices

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:46.130 align:middle line:84%
with the higher
aggregate expenditure.

00:15:46.130 --> 00:15:51.620 align:middle line:84%
Then, the next step is to
review the definition of profit

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:55.130 align:middle line:84%
maximization in a
competitive equilibrium,

00:15:55.130 --> 00:15:59.720 align:middle line:84%
meaning at yj star, the
valuation of profits

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:03.830 align:middle line:84%
is not less than
any other feasible--

00:16:03.830 --> 00:16:09.290 align:middle line:84%
technologically
feasible vector yj.

00:16:09.290 --> 00:16:14.310 align:middle line:84%
And this is true for each firm
j, hence true for all of them.

00:16:14.310 --> 00:16:17.120 align:middle line:90%
So we can sum up over them.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:21.440 align:middle line:84%
And now we take this
statement for firms

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:24.980 align:middle line:84%
with the statement on the
previous slide for households

00:16:24.980 --> 00:16:27.420 align:middle line:84%
and start using them
both simultaneously.

00:16:27.420 --> 00:16:32.860 align:middle line:84%
So from the previous slide,
we have the summation over I

00:16:32.860 --> 00:16:36.880 align:middle line:90%
pxi strictly dominates pxi star.

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:41.380 align:middle line:84%
But we also had a competitive
equilibrium given to us

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:46.210 align:middle line:84%
as an initial condition,
therefore feasible.

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:52.630 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, xi star is equal
to omega bar plus y star.

00:16:52.630 --> 00:16:54.440 align:middle line:90%
And I should have pointed out.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:57.670 align:middle line:84%
I think I just skipped
over it too fast.

00:16:57.670 --> 00:17:00.190 align:middle line:84%
It's easiest to
think about prices

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:02.600 align:middle line:90%
as being strictly positive.

00:17:02.600 --> 00:17:08.450 align:middle line:84%
So the only algebra going on
here is to take dot products,

00:17:08.450 --> 00:17:12.500 align:middle line:84%
take prices, put it
outside the parentheses,

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:15.349 align:middle line:84%
then collect terms,
put it back inside.

00:17:15.349 --> 00:17:21.619 align:middle line:84%
So p dot xi, summation
over I, but Xi

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:25.560 align:middle line:84%
is equal to a omega
bar plus yj star.

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:29.660 align:middle line:84%
So if we put p outside and
then multiplied it inside,

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:35.130 align:middle line:84%
we get price times the
odd quantity object

00:17:35.130 --> 00:17:37.020 align:middle line:90%
in each of the two terms.

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:39.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, this last inequality
is the statement

00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:41.490 align:middle line:90%
of profit maximization.

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:45.600 align:middle line:84%
Holding the valuation of the
aggregate endowment of fixed py

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:51.060 align:middle line:90%
star j is no less than pyj.

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:54.240 align:middle line:84%
And so now, we
again do this trick.

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:57.480 align:middle line:84%
We take prices, put
in on the outside,

00:17:57.480 --> 00:18:01.200 align:middle line:84%
and look at all terms
inside the parentheses,

00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:07.650 align:middle line:84%
and we've got the Xi over here
and the omega bar and the yj

00:18:07.650 --> 00:18:08.230 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:18:08.230 --> 00:18:10.200 align:middle line:84%
So we collect those
terms together,

00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:11.970 align:middle line:90%
and we get this statement.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:14.280 align:middle line:84%
But if this is
greater than this,

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:17.610 align:middle line:84%
then when you subtract
them, it's greater than 0.

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:20.850 align:middle line:84%
So we finally arrive
at the contradiction.

00:18:20.850 --> 00:18:21.840 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:26.690 align:middle line:84%
Because this supposedly
Pareto-dominating point

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:29.330 align:middle line:84%
has to be feasible in
the sense of the resource

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:34.560 align:middle line:84%
constraint, which means this
has to be 0 for each component.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:39.510 align:middle line:84%
But by the argument achieved, it
can't be 0 for every component

00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:42.310 align:middle line:84%
or this could not
be greater than 0.

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:45.490 align:middle line:84%
So it is not true
that it's feasible,

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:48.390 align:middle line:90%
and that's the contradiction.

00:18:48.390 --> 00:18:51.970 align:middle line:84%
So it's a big proof
by contradiction.

00:18:51.970 --> 00:18:54.015 align:middle line:84%
So something's
happening along the way.

00:18:54.015 --> 00:18:59.390 align:middle line:90%


00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:02.370 align:middle line:84%
We're going to go to the
second welfare theorem now.

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:07.280 align:middle line:84%
Any Pareto-optimal
allocation can be implemented

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:11.390 align:middle line:90%
as a competitive equilibrium.

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:13.020 align:middle line:90%
We can come back to this slide.

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:14.710 align:middle line:90%
But here's the picture.

00:19:14.710 --> 00:19:18.970 align:middle line:84%
So we pick another
Pareto-optimal point

00:19:18.970 --> 00:19:21.720 align:middle line:90%
in that Edgeworth box.

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:24.660 align:middle line:84%
Not this one that ran
through the endowment,

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:27.920 align:middle line:90%
but something southwest of it.

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:28.920 align:middle line:90%
So here's the endowment.

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:30.700 align:middle line:90%
It's still there.

00:19:30.700 --> 00:19:33.540 align:middle line:84%
But now we're targeting
this other Pareto-optimal

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:35.920 align:middle line:90%
allocation.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:39.070 align:middle line:84%
And the theorem
says there's a way

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:42.790 align:middle line:84%
to redistribute wealth in
such a way to achieve it.

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:44.920 align:middle line:84%
Note the marginal
rates of substitution

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:48.520 align:middle line:84%
all match up for
Agent A and Agent B.

00:19:48.520 --> 00:19:50.620 align:middle line:90%
They're equal to sum price.

00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:54.880 align:middle line:84%
The price, p1 over p2,
is captured by the slope

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:58.570 align:middle line:90%
of that, quote, "budget line."

00:19:58.570 --> 00:20:01.360 align:middle line:84%
But I really want
to say wealth line

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:05.740 align:middle line:84%
because it is not a line that
runs through the privately

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:07.800 align:middle line:90%
owned endowments.

00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:10.280 align:middle line:84%
So the previous slide,
which I skipped,

00:20:10.280 --> 00:20:14.810 align:middle line:84%
just says that those star
allocations for A and B

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:18.560 align:middle line:84%
have the same slopes, which
are their marginal rates

00:20:18.560 --> 00:20:20.030 align:middle line:90%
of substitution.

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:22.100 align:middle line:84%
And the marginal
rates of substitution

00:20:22.100 --> 00:20:24.500 align:middle line:84%
match up since they're
equal to each other.

00:20:24.500 --> 00:20:25.880 align:middle line:90%
Just something called gamma.

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:27.830 align:middle line:90%
So that's the picture here.

00:20:27.830 --> 00:20:30.440 align:middle line:84%
Margin rates of
substitution are equal,

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:33.290 align:middle line:84%
equal to the slope of
this wealth line, which

00:20:33.290 --> 00:20:36.670 align:middle line:90%
has a slope of gamma.

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:41.360 align:middle line:84%
Now, the point is that
if they had started

00:20:41.360 --> 00:20:47.760 align:middle line:84%
from the endowment, this
thing, agent B would not

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:52.740 align:middle line:84%
have enough wealth to get to
this Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:20:52.740 --> 00:20:55.500 align:middle line:84%
Conceptually, imagining
somehow the slopes

00:20:55.500 --> 00:21:01.080 align:middle line:84%
were the same if we had
drawn at those prices

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:05.790 align:middle line:84%
gamma line, a budget line
going through the endowment,

00:21:05.790 --> 00:21:07.680 align:middle line:90%
Agent B has to be further out.

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:09.570 align:middle line:90%
He has to have more wealth.

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:11.920 align:middle line:84%
And where does that
wealth come from?

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:18.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, Mr. A over here
gets to make the sacrifice

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:23.950 align:middle line:84%
because he has gone southwest
of where he would be in terms

00:21:23.950 --> 00:21:26.410 align:middle line:84%
of the budget line through
the endowment if we insisted

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:29.290 align:middle line:84%
that didn't go
through the endowment.

00:21:29.290 --> 00:21:32.130 align:middle line:84%
So all of that is
summarized on this slide.

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:36.390 align:middle line:84%
If we start out with
that price ratio--

00:21:36.390 --> 00:21:38.310 align:middle line:90%
by the way, gamma 1, why?

00:21:38.310 --> 00:21:43.300 align:middle line:84%
Because the slope of
this thing is p1 over p2.

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:46.420 align:middle line:84%
So we might as well set p2
equal to 1 as the numerator

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:49.360 align:middle line:84%
because we're not
going to get any more

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:51.790 align:middle line:90%
determination than that.

00:21:51.790 --> 00:21:54.880 align:middle line:84%
So it looks weird when
you write it like this,

00:21:54.880 --> 00:22:00.506 align:middle line:84%
but p equal p1 equal
gamma p2 equal to 1

00:22:00.506 --> 00:22:03.710 align:middle line:90%
are the prices we need.

00:22:03.710 --> 00:22:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Agents are going to
maximize at those prices,

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:11.720 align:middle line:84%
depending on what
their wealth is.

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:17.570 align:middle line:84%
But the allocation at
those prices for Agent B

00:22:17.570 --> 00:22:22.520 align:middle line:84%
costs more than the valuation
of Agent B's endowment

00:22:22.520 --> 00:22:27.260 align:middle line:90%
at the price gamma 1.

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:30.110 align:middle line:84%
So what we propose
to do to Agent

00:22:30.110 --> 00:22:34.460 align:middle line:84%
B is to give them
the difference,

00:22:34.460 --> 00:22:37.250 align:middle line:84%
just give them
enough extra wealth

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:43.080 align:middle line:84%
so that Agent B can afford
to buy the star bundle, which

00:22:43.080 --> 00:22:46.980 align:middle line:84%
requires more than the
valuation of his wealth

00:22:46.980 --> 00:22:49.770 align:middle line:90%
at his previous endowment.

00:22:49.770 --> 00:22:53.520 align:middle line:84%
So we call this a transfer
to B. And it's positive,

00:22:53.520 --> 00:22:56.310 align:middle line:84%
as you could see
from that diagram.

00:22:56.310 --> 00:22:58.050 align:middle line:90%
And A makes the sacrifice.

00:22:58.050 --> 00:23:02.710 align:middle line:90%


00:23:02.710 --> 00:23:04.655 align:middle line:90%
There seems to be a typo here.

00:23:04.655 --> 00:23:09.510 align:middle line:90%


00:23:09.510 --> 00:23:13.670 align:middle line:84%
It's probably--
anyway, you can see it.

00:23:13.670 --> 00:23:16.030 align:middle line:90%
The wealth transfer is the same.

00:23:16.030 --> 00:23:20.790 align:middle line:84%
It goes from B to A, and
this is written oddly

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:24.360 align:middle line:84%
as if it were B's endowment
and B's expenditure.

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:27.120 align:middle line:84%
But it's really referring
to the point on the box

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:31.770 align:middle line:84%
here, which is simultaneously
the point for B and for A.

00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:38.460 align:middle line:84%
And so we just move southwest,
taxing A, and giving the tax

00:23:38.460 --> 00:23:41.760 align:middle line:90%
to B as a physical transfer.

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:45.000 align:middle line:84%
So we found a price
equilibrium with transfers

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:49.080 align:middle line:84%
that will support that target
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:52.090 align:middle line:84%
And it's possible to
do any one of them.

00:23:52.090 --> 00:23:55.660 align:middle line:84%
So if you go back here, this
was the private ownership Pareto

00:23:55.660 --> 00:23:56.520 align:middle line:90%
optimum.

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:59.070 align:middle line:84%
There are all these other
Pareto-optimal allocations.

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:04.740 align:middle line:84%
The theorem says, give me any
Pareto-optimal allocation,

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:08.550 align:middle line:84%
and I can redistribute
wealth in such a way

00:24:08.550 --> 00:24:11.620 align:middle line:84%
as to support it as a
competitive equilibrium

00:24:11.620 --> 00:24:13.020 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:24:13.020 --> 00:24:16.200 align:middle line:84%
Who gets taxed and who gets
the transfers depends on which

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:20.170 align:middle line:84%
optimum we have
under consideration.

00:24:20.170 --> 00:24:24.640 align:middle line:90%
So this one takes more.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:29.250 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have to start
assuming stuff for the theorem

00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:30.090 align:middle line:90%
to be--

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:34.470 align:middle line:84%
for sufficient conditions
for the theorem to be true.

00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:39.150 align:middle line:84%
We start with the
notation of our economy.

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:46.710 align:middle line:84%
Consumption sets for the agents,
utility functions, endowments,

00:24:46.710 --> 00:24:52.650 align:middle line:84%
production sets, shares
in ownership of profits,

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:56.190 align:middle line:84%
which is a quick review of the
notation you've seen before.

00:24:56.190 --> 00:24:59.420 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have to
assume that these consumption

00:24:59.420 --> 00:25:04.880 align:middle line:84%
sets essentially can be
formed by combinations

00:25:04.880 --> 00:25:06.690 align:middle line:90%
of quasi-concave functions.

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:10.370 align:middle line:84%
This first line is
the most awkward.

00:25:10.370 --> 00:25:13.220 align:middle line:84%
And if you wish,
you could just think

00:25:13.220 --> 00:25:20.090 align:middle line:84%
about these being the
non-negative orthant,

00:25:20.090 --> 00:25:24.940 align:middle line:84%
that any positive
consumption bundle is fine.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:27.100 align:middle line:84%
I only put the most
general version

00:25:27.100 --> 00:25:31.600 align:middle line:84%
because I want to emphasize you
need restrictions on things.

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:35.860 align:middle line:84%
Here's a statement about
the production sets.

00:25:35.860 --> 00:25:40.750 align:middle line:84%
Production sets Yj admit
a concave transformation

00:25:40.750 --> 00:25:42.760 align:middle line:90%
function called F.

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:44.570 align:middle line:90%
What the heck does that mean?

00:25:44.570 --> 00:25:49.600 align:middle line:84%
Well, it means that for any
vector Y in the production set,

00:25:49.600 --> 00:25:52.870 align:middle line:84%
it can be represented
through some function

00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:58.480 align:middle line:84%
F, which is non-negative
when evaluated at that Y.

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:01.960 align:middle line:84%
An example, because
this is really obscure,

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:05.950 align:middle line:84%
suppose we have
an input z mapped

00:26:05.950 --> 00:26:11.070 align:middle line:84%
through production function
little f to get output q.

00:26:11.070 --> 00:26:13.370 align:middle line:84%
And we throw away
some of the output.

00:26:13.370 --> 00:26:16.880 align:middle line:84%
So we're not on the frontier,
we're in the interior.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:23.814 align:middle line:84%
Then if you rewrite this as f
of z minus q, it's non-negative.

00:26:23.814 --> 00:26:26.470 align:middle line:90%


00:26:26.470 --> 00:26:34.520 align:middle line:84%
So any input-output
combination, zq,

00:26:34.520 --> 00:26:38.030 align:middle line:84%
when evaluated under F,
which takes this form,

00:26:38.030 --> 00:26:41.140 align:middle line:90%
is non-negative.

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:44.260 align:middle line:90%
So it really is quite innocuous.

