00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:14.720 align:middle line:90%
That's this.

00:39:14.720 --> 00:39:16.250 align:middle line:90%
So we're given this.

00:39:16.250 --> 00:39:20.570 align:middle line:84%
And we want to find Lagrange
multipliers mu and prices

00:39:20.570 --> 00:39:24.320 align:middle line:84%
p so as to satisfy this
optimizing first-order

00:39:24.320 --> 00:39:27.980 align:middle line:84%
condition per household i in
the competitive equilibrium

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:28.940 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:39:28.940 --> 00:39:31.400 align:middle line:90%
Now, what would you guess?

00:39:31.400 --> 00:39:34.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, we want-- this is
true, and we want this.

00:39:34.780 --> 00:39:38.560 align:middle line:84%
So let's guess that the
price that we want is

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:43.110 align:middle line:84%
the gamma, Lagrange multiplier
on the resource constraint

00:39:43.110 --> 00:39:45.010 align:middle line:90%
for good l.

00:39:45.010 --> 00:39:47.380 align:middle line:90%
Pl equal gamma l.

00:39:47.380 --> 00:39:50.440 align:middle line:84%
And let's guess that the
mu that we want to find

00:39:50.440 --> 00:39:52.720 align:middle line:90%
is simply 1 over lambda i.

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:55.750 align:middle line:84%
That's down here
summarized at the bottom.

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.290 align:middle line:84%
And the final guess would be
that the wealth allocation

00:39:59.290 --> 00:40:02.050 align:middle line:84%
that we need in the
Pareto-optimal allocation

00:40:02.050 --> 00:40:05.650 align:middle line:84%
is just the valuation
of expenditures

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:08.650 align:middle line:84%
at that Pareto-optimal
allocation.

00:40:08.650 --> 00:40:11.380 align:middle line:90%
I use my words carefully here.

00:40:11.380 --> 00:40:15.580 align:middle line:84%
The valuation, though, is at
the shadow prices gamma l.

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:18.700 align:middle line:84%
If you go back to
the Pareto problem,

00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:22.630 align:middle line:84%
these gammas were arbitrary
Lagrange multipliers

00:40:22.630 --> 00:40:25.620 align:middle line:90%
on the resource constraint.

00:40:25.620 --> 00:40:28.250 align:middle line:84%
And we went to the math of all
the first-order conditions.

00:40:28.250 --> 00:40:31.940 align:middle line:84%
But really, what
it is, is how much

00:40:31.940 --> 00:40:38.620 align:middle line:84%
the solution that shadow price
reflects the incremental gain

00:40:38.620 --> 00:40:44.410 align:middle line:84%
in the objective function
to weakening the resource

00:40:44.410 --> 00:40:48.380 align:middle line:90%
constraint by a teeny amount.

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:50.350 align:middle line:90%
So it is like a shadow price.

00:40:50.350 --> 00:40:53.690 align:middle line:84%
We often call the Lagrange
multiplier shadow prices.

00:40:53.690 --> 00:40:56.800 align:middle line:84%
It's really marginal
utility pricing

00:40:56.800 --> 00:41:00.520 align:middle line:84%
because we're incrementing
the weighted sum of utilities

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:07.400 align:middle line:84%
a bit, hence like a derivative,
as we weaken the constraint.

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:12.830 align:middle line:84%
So it's natural really that
these Lagrange multipliers l,

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:15.770 align:middle line:84%
for good l, should
be shadow prices.

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:19.490 align:middle line:84%
And the actual competitive
equilibrium prices

00:41:19.490 --> 00:41:22.430 align:middle line:84%
in the corresponding while
raising in equilibrium

00:41:22.430 --> 00:41:24.560 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:41:24.560 --> 00:41:27.650 align:middle line:84%
This thing down here,
very simply written,

00:41:27.650 --> 00:41:31.790 align:middle line:90%
is that mu i is 1 over lambda i.

00:41:31.790 --> 00:41:32.750 align:middle line:90%
Oh, who cares?

00:41:32.750 --> 00:41:34.130 align:middle line:90%
No, no, no, no, no, no.

00:41:34.130 --> 00:41:35.930 align:middle line:90%
Don't think of it that way.

00:41:35.930 --> 00:41:38.210 align:middle line:84%
Think of those beautiful
graphs of Kansas

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:40.310 align:middle line:90%
and so on at the beginning.

00:41:40.310 --> 00:41:41.300 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:44.870 align:middle line:84%
So what this is
saying is mu i, which

00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:46.790 align:middle line:84%
is the marginal
utility of income,

00:41:46.790 --> 00:41:53.408 align:middle line:84%
the marginal utility of wealth
in the target competitive--

00:41:53.408 --> 00:41:55.200 align:middle line:84%
we're raising an
equilibrium with transfers

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:56.580 align:middle line:90%
that we're trying to find.

00:41:56.580 --> 00:42:03.070 align:middle line:84%
The marginal utility of
wealth at that location

00:42:03.070 --> 00:42:07.670 align:middle line:84%
is inversely related to the
lambda weights in the Pareto

00:42:07.670 --> 00:42:08.170 align:middle line:90%
problem.

00:42:08.170 --> 00:42:11.080 align:middle line:90%


00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:13.990 align:middle line:84%
So the higher the
lambda weights,

00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:18.150 align:middle line:84%
the lower would be the
marginal utility of wealth.

00:42:18.150 --> 00:42:21.070 align:middle line:90%


00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:24.640 align:middle line:84%
Remember the first
two slides, I told you

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:27.670 align:middle line:84%
that the gradient in
the consumption profile

00:42:27.670 --> 00:42:30.340 align:middle line:84%
had something to do
with the lambda weights.

00:42:30.340 --> 00:42:32.140 align:middle line:84%
And we could look
in the data to see

00:42:32.140 --> 00:42:33.535 align:middle line:90%
if it was related to wealth.

00:42:33.535 --> 00:42:36.290 align:middle line:90%


00:42:36.290 --> 00:42:38.140 align:middle line:84%
So this may look
upside down, but that's

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:41.620 align:middle line:84%
only because mu i is the
marginal utility of wealth.

00:42:41.620 --> 00:42:45.410 align:middle line:84%
As wealth goes up,
marginal utility goes down.

00:42:45.410 --> 00:42:47.380 align:middle line:84%
So as lambda goes
up, and they're

00:42:47.380 --> 00:42:50.740 align:middle line:84%
more favored in
the Pareto problem,

00:42:50.740 --> 00:42:53.350 align:middle line:84%
the marginal utility of
wealth is going down.

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:55.370 align:middle line:90%
And how does that happen?

00:42:55.370 --> 00:42:59.700 align:middle line:84%
It happens because
they get more wealth.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:06.060 align:middle line:84%
So there's kind of a 1 to 1
mapping, a monotone mapping,

00:43:06.060 --> 00:43:08.350 align:middle line:84%
between the lambdas
in the Pareto problem

00:43:08.350 --> 00:43:12.890 align:middle line:84%
and the wealth that corresponds
to the competitive equilibrium

00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:14.960 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:18.870 align:middle line:84%
And here it is falling
out in a very elegant way.

00:43:18.870 --> 00:43:22.300 align:middle line:90%


00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:25.770 align:middle line:84%
And this other thing at
the bottom, that Wi star,

00:43:25.770 --> 00:43:27.870 align:middle line:84%
is the valuation
of expenditures.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:33.450 align:middle line:84%
Again, that's pretty much
what we were doing in the box.

00:43:33.450 --> 00:43:36.090 align:middle line:84%
We took a target
allocation here,

00:43:36.090 --> 00:43:39.120 align:middle line:84%
that it wasn't a
competitive equilibrium

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:40.740 align:middle line:90%
with private ownership.

00:43:40.740 --> 00:43:45.120 align:middle line:84%
But we could tax A
and transfer to B

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:51.000 align:middle line:84%
so these stars here represented
the target Pareto-optimal

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:52.450 align:middle line:90%
allocation.

00:43:52.450 --> 00:43:57.030 align:middle line:84%
And we're valuating
those expenditures

00:43:57.030 --> 00:44:02.080 align:middle line:84%
at the prices corresponding
to the budget line.

00:44:02.080 --> 00:44:04.530 align:middle line:84%
So you can start
them out with wealth

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:09.280 align:middle line:84%
being at carefully
chosen prices,

00:44:09.280 --> 00:44:15.430 align:middle line:84%
the valuation of the star
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:18.430 align:middle line:84%
And that's this part
here at the bottom,

00:44:18.430 --> 00:44:20.230 align:middle line:84%
that the wealth
we give to Agent I

00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:24.790 align:middle line:84%
is just the valuation of the
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:44:24.790 --> 00:44:28.450 align:middle line:84%
Now also is utility
maximizing allocation

00:44:28.450 --> 00:44:32.270 align:middle line:90%
at the prices gamma, gamma star.

00:44:32.270 --> 00:44:35.390 align:middle line:90%
We did all that for consumption.

00:44:35.390 --> 00:44:38.900 align:middle line:84%
Something else happens
automatically along the way,

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:43.470 align:middle line:84%
namely when you look at
those first-order conditions,

00:44:43.470 --> 00:44:46.290 align:middle line:84%
we can define the marginal
rate of substitution

00:44:46.290 --> 00:44:52.550 align:middle line:84%
of good l for good k for agent
I. The lambdas cancel out,

00:44:52.550 --> 00:44:53.050 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:44:53.050 --> 00:44:56.980 align:middle line:84%
It's lambda I for a
household i for any good l.

00:44:56.980 --> 00:44:58.990 align:middle line:84%
So if we take the
derivative of utility

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:04.900 align:middle line:84%
with respect to the two
goods, in this case l and k,

00:45:04.900 --> 00:45:08.330 align:middle line:84%
the lambda is in the numerator
and denominator it cancels out.

00:45:08.330 --> 00:45:13.860 align:middle line:84%
So this is the marginal rate
of substitution corresponding

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:16.350 align:middle line:84%
to these optimizing first-order
conditions for household

00:45:16.350 --> 00:45:19.065 align:middle line:90%
I's, obviously equal to--

00:45:19.065 --> 00:45:23.240 align:middle line:90%


00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:25.730 align:middle line:84%
the I's, as I said,
are canceling out,

00:45:25.730 --> 00:45:33.510 align:middle line:84%
equal to the ratio of prices,
back to some other household h.

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:37.440 align:middle line:84%
So this is the math of what
you already saw in the picture

00:45:37.440 --> 00:45:40.890 align:middle line:84%
that I've shown you three
times, the marginal rates

00:45:40.890 --> 00:45:43.440 align:middle line:84%
of substitution are
equated across households

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:46.350 align:middle line:84%
and equal to the
common price ratio.

00:45:46.350 --> 00:45:49.320 align:middle line:84%
All of that coming from
the first-order conditions

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:52.980 align:middle line:90%
that we've now formally derived.

00:45:52.980 --> 00:45:55.810 align:middle line:90%
One more step, firms.

00:45:55.810 --> 00:45:59.200 align:middle line:90%
So we have profit maximization.

00:45:59.200 --> 00:46:01.990 align:middle line:90%
Oh, are you lost again?

00:46:01.990 --> 00:46:05.950 align:middle line:84%
I say that a bit tongue in
cheek because everything

00:46:05.950 --> 00:46:07.553 align:middle line:84%
is equivalent to
everything else.

00:46:07.553 --> 00:46:08.970 align:middle line:84%
And it's easy to
get turned around

00:46:08.970 --> 00:46:11.240 align:middle line:90%
and forget our starting point.

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:14.530 align:middle line:84%
So we started with a
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:46:14.530 --> 00:46:16.600 align:middle line:84%
We looked at the first-order
conditions, which

00:46:16.600 --> 00:46:19.040 align:middle line:90%
are necessary and sufficient.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:24.140 align:middle line:90%
And we got this thing.

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:27.190 align:middle line:90%
So this is true.

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:29.500 align:middle line:84%
Now, we want to find the
conditions for profit

00:46:29.500 --> 00:46:33.340 align:middle line:84%
maximization in a competitive
equilibrium with transfers.

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:38.800 align:middle line:84%
So we want this equation
to be satisfied.

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:43.510 align:middle line:84%
As long as we can choose
the gammas and the piece

00:46:43.510 --> 00:46:46.840 align:middle line:84%
appropriately, we'll be done,
and it's easy to choose them.

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:49.570 align:middle line:84%
P, we already
pinned down already.

00:46:49.570 --> 00:46:50.530 align:middle line:90%
p sub l.

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:53.770 align:middle line:84%
The price of good l
is the shadow price

00:46:53.770 --> 00:46:56.590 align:middle line:90%
derived previously gamma l.

00:46:56.590 --> 00:46:59.980 align:middle line:84%
And it just remains to figure
out what this delta l is.

00:46:59.980 --> 00:47:03.790 align:middle line:84%
Can we find that Lagrange
multiplier somehow?

00:47:03.790 --> 00:47:04.390 align:middle line:90%
Searching?

00:47:04.390 --> 00:47:04.900 align:middle line:90%
Sure.

00:47:04.900 --> 00:47:08.200 align:middle line:84%
Let's let it equal to
the associated Lagrange

00:47:08.200 --> 00:47:12.230 align:middle line:84%
multiplier and the solution
to the Pareto problem.

00:47:12.230 --> 00:47:14.660 align:middle line:90%
And again, because all these--

00:47:14.660 --> 00:47:18.740 align:middle line:84%
if you can satisfy this because
it's necessary and sufficient,

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:21.350 align:middle line:90%
then we have profit max.

00:47:21.350 --> 00:47:27.560 align:middle line:84%
So we just pick the delta
and the p to be what--

00:47:27.560 --> 00:47:30.560 align:middle line:84%
obviously, it would
be true so that we

00:47:30.560 --> 00:47:33.730 align:middle line:90%
have profit maximization.

00:47:33.730 --> 00:47:35.010 align:middle line:90%
So we're almost there.

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:37.680 align:middle line:90%
We have a solution.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:40.090 align:middle line:84%
We started with a target
Pareto-optimal allocation.

00:47:40.090 --> 00:47:42.960 align:middle line:84%
We have a solution to
the household problem

00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:45.750 align:middle line:84%
in the competitive
equilibrium with transfers.

00:47:45.750 --> 00:47:48.200 align:middle line:84%
We have a solution
to the first problem.

00:47:48.200 --> 00:47:49.950 align:middle line:84%
So what do we know
about feasibility,

00:47:49.950 --> 00:47:55.080 align:middle line:84%
and what do we know about
the allocation of wealth?

00:47:55.080 --> 00:47:59.520 align:middle line:84%
So we know what householdized
wealth has to be,

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:00.510 align:middle line:90%
as I've been saying.

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:06.990 align:middle line:84%
It's just the valuation of
the assignment, the Xi star

00:48:06.990 --> 00:48:12.380 align:middle line:84%
assignment in the Pareto problem
at the prices gamma equal to p.

00:48:12.380 --> 00:48:14.150 align:middle line:84%
So that's the wealth
of household I.

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:16.235 align:middle line:84%
Let's sum them up and
make sure it's feasible.

00:48:16.235 --> 00:48:19.040 align:middle line:90%


00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:25.990 align:middle line:84%
So we sum up the valuation
of the target at prices p.

00:48:25.990 --> 00:48:27.910 align:middle line:90%
But now we do this trick.

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:29.320 align:middle line:90%
Bring p outside.

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:30.940 align:middle line:90%
It's common.

00:48:30.940 --> 00:48:35.380 align:middle line:84%
I suppose it's strictly positive
in all the components too,

00:48:35.380 --> 00:48:37.270 align:middle line:90%
just to make it easy.

00:48:37.270 --> 00:48:41.290 align:middle line:84%
Then, this summation
of-- because of we

00:48:41.290 --> 00:48:44.050 align:middle line:84%
started with a
Pareto optimum, so it

00:48:44.050 --> 00:48:46.520 align:middle line:90%
had to be resource feasible.

00:48:46.520 --> 00:48:51.950 align:middle line:84%
So now, we use that fact, that
the summation over i Xi star

00:48:51.950 --> 00:48:55.400 align:middle line:84%
must be equal to
the summation over i

00:48:55.400 --> 00:49:00.330 align:middle line:90%
of the endowment plus output.

00:49:00.330 --> 00:49:03.200 align:middle line:90%
So demand is equal to supply.

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:06.290 align:middle line:84%
Demand is equal to
endowments plus production.

00:49:06.290 --> 00:49:09.220 align:middle line:90%


00:49:09.220 --> 00:49:16.640 align:middle line:84%
And then, you can
rewrite the p dot yj's

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:20.110 align:middle line:84%
to be consistent with the
claim on those profits

00:49:20.110 --> 00:49:24.770 align:middle line:84%
under these ownership
shares, theta ij.

00:49:24.770 --> 00:49:27.680 align:middle line:84%
It probably would have
been clearer if p were also

00:49:27.680 --> 00:49:29.700 align:middle line:90%
still multiplying each part.

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:30.380 align:middle line:90%
But it's there.

00:49:30.380 --> 00:49:33.140 align:middle line:84%
It's just outside
the parentheses.

00:49:33.140 --> 00:49:35.930 align:middle line:90%
And then, we group--

00:49:35.930 --> 00:49:38.750 align:middle line:84%
finally, we do put
the p's on the inside.

00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:42.420 align:middle line:84%
And we have what we
want because this

00:49:42.420 --> 00:49:44.940 align:middle line:90%
is total wealth in the economy.

00:49:44.940 --> 00:49:46.110 align:middle line:90%
It's the total value.

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:48.390 align:middle line:84%
It's the valuation of
the aggregate endowment

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:51.140 align:middle line:90%
plus profits.

00:49:51.140 --> 00:49:56.540 align:middle line:84%
And it adds up to the
sum of the wealths

00:49:56.540 --> 00:50:01.460 align:middle line:84%
that we need, according to
the solutions to the consumer

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:03.180 align:middle line:90%
maximization problem.

00:50:03.180 --> 00:50:04.970 align:middle line:90%
So now we're done.

00:50:04.970 --> 00:50:07.273 align:middle line:84%
This last slide is
always a bit mysterious.

00:50:07.273 --> 00:50:09.440 align:middle line:84%
It's like, well, why do we
have to do anything else?

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:12.170 align:middle line:84%
Well, again, just
remember the definition

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:14.480 align:middle line:84%
of a competitive
equilibrium with transfers.

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:16.940 align:middle line:84%
Because it's transfers,
it's specified

00:50:16.940 --> 00:50:18.590 align:middle line:84%
not in terms of
private ownership

00:50:18.590 --> 00:50:20.000 align:middle line:90%
but in terms of wealth.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.680 align:middle line:84%
So whatever those
wealths are, they

00:50:21.680 --> 00:50:24.590 align:middle line:90%
have to add up to the total.

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:27.880 align:middle line:84%
That's what this
slide is all about.

00:50:27.880 --> 00:50:31.680 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we call
the constructive proof,

00:50:31.680 --> 00:50:37.560 align:middle line:84%
is just using finite
dimensional Euclidean spaces,

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:40.680 align:middle line:84%
putting in a lot of concavity,
convexity, et cetera,

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:43.740 align:middle line:84%
then sort of matching up
first-order conditions.

00:50:43.740 --> 00:50:46.260 align:middle line:84%
But the theorem
holds more generally.

00:50:46.260 --> 00:50:48.960 align:middle line:84%
The second welfare
theorem is true,

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:52.650 align:middle line:84%
even without making special
assumptions about the commodity

00:50:52.650 --> 00:50:54.330 align:middle line:90%
space and so on.

00:50:54.330 --> 00:50:56.010 align:middle line:84%
A step along the
way is something

00:50:56.010 --> 00:51:00.360 align:middle line:84%
called the quasi-equilibrium
with transfers, quasi

00:51:00.360 --> 00:51:05.430 align:middle line:84%
meaning it's not quite
fully consumer maximization.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:07.690 align:middle line:90%
But it's going to be close.

00:51:07.690 --> 00:51:09.480 align:middle line:90%
So here's the definition.

00:51:09.480 --> 00:51:14.520 align:middle line:84%
An allocation, x star, y
star and a price vector p,

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:17.130 align:middle line:84%
constitute a price
quasi-equilibrium

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:20.940 align:middle line:84%
with transfers if we can
find wealth levels that

00:51:20.940 --> 00:51:24.030 align:middle line:84%
add up to the total
wealth if each firm

00:51:24.030 --> 00:51:25.960 align:middle line:90%
J is profit maximizing.

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:26.760 align:middle line:90%
So far so good.

00:51:26.760 --> 00:51:28.090 align:middle line:90%
Nothing different.

00:51:28.090 --> 00:51:29.400 align:middle line:90%
Here's the difference.

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:32.670 align:middle line:84%
Household i, this
condition has to be true.

00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:37.230 align:middle line:84%
If Xi star is the
allocation we want

00:51:37.230 --> 00:51:40.950 align:middle line:84%
in the definition of the
equilibrium with transfer price

00:51:40.950 --> 00:51:43.470 align:middle line:84%
quasi-equilibrium
with transfers,

00:51:43.470 --> 00:51:46.620 align:middle line:84%
if you start with
that Xi star and there

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:48.570 align:middle line:84%
were an allocation
that's strictly

00:51:48.570 --> 00:51:54.840 align:middle line:84%
better for household i, then
it costs at least as much

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:58.350 align:middle line:84%
as the wealth assignment in
the price quasi-equilibrium

00:51:58.350 --> 00:51:59.050 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:00.420 align:middle line:90%
It's kind of a mouthful.

00:52:00.420 --> 00:52:04.530 align:middle line:84%
One way to put this,
though, is that Wi star

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:08.640 align:middle line:84%
is the valuation of
expenditures at the equilibrium,

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:10.860 align:middle line:90%
at the equilibrium Xi star.

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:14.820 align:middle line:84%
So then this says pxi, the
valuation of this arbitrary

00:52:14.820 --> 00:52:17.940 align:middle line:84%
Xi, which is strictly
preferred, the valuation

00:52:17.940 --> 00:52:22.200 align:middle line:84%
is not less than the
valuation of pxi star.

00:52:22.200 --> 00:52:26.310 align:middle line:84%
That means that pxi
star costs no more

00:52:26.310 --> 00:52:30.930 align:middle line:84%
or is cost minimizing
over the upper contour

00:52:30.930 --> 00:52:33.330 align:middle line:84%
set of allocations
that are associated

00:52:33.330 --> 00:52:35.280 align:middle line:90%
with strictly more utility.

00:52:35.280 --> 00:52:38.175 align:middle line:84%
So you've seen this
before, way back when.

00:52:38.175 --> 00:52:41.970 align:middle line:84%
When we did the consumer
utility maximization problem,

00:52:41.970 --> 00:52:44.490 align:middle line:84%
I pointed out that this
is kind of a dual thing.

00:52:44.490 --> 00:52:47.280 align:middle line:84%
Instead of maximizing
utility subject to budgets,

00:52:47.280 --> 00:52:51.090 align:middle line:84%
we minimized the budget
necessary to achieve

00:52:51.090 --> 00:52:52.710 align:middle line:90%
a given level of utility.

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:54.540 align:middle line:90%
In fact, we did a lot with that.

00:52:54.540 --> 00:52:59.860 align:middle line:84%
We did Hicksian substitutions
versus Walrasian substitutions

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:00.360 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:53:00.360 --> 00:53:02.560 align:middle line:90%
We had a whole lecture on it.

00:53:02.560 --> 00:53:04.680 align:middle line:84%
So here it is again,
except so instead

00:53:04.680 --> 00:53:07.410 align:middle line:84%
of assuming utility
maximization,

00:53:07.410 --> 00:53:09.900 align:middle line:84%
we're going to assume
cost minimization.

00:53:09.900 --> 00:53:13.620 align:middle line:84%
That's the only difference
between a regular equilibrium

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:15.960 align:middle line:84%
with transfers and
this quasi-equilibrium

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:16.650 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:53:16.650 --> 00:53:21.010 align:middle line:84%
The feasibility of the
allocation is the same.

00:53:21.010 --> 00:53:23.130 align:middle line:84%
So I'll show you
the theorems now.

00:53:23.130 --> 00:53:27.660 align:middle line:84%
But just to say, when we do
the second welfare theorem,

00:53:27.660 --> 00:53:31.230 align:middle line:84%
we're going to say that it's
a price quasi-equilibrium

00:53:31.230 --> 00:53:32.130 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:53:32.130 --> 00:53:34.570 align:middle line:84%
And then, given the
structure of the economy,

00:53:34.570 --> 00:53:37.140 align:middle line:84%
you may need a little
bit more to establish

00:53:37.140 --> 00:53:39.780 align:middle line:84%
that cost minimization
corresponds

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:42.090 align:middle line:90%
with utility maximization.

00:53:42.090 --> 00:53:45.900 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that the production
sets are strict or convex,

00:53:45.900 --> 00:53:48.720 align:middle line:84%
the preference relations
are rational convex

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:51.390 align:middle line:84%
and satisfy local
nonsatiation, then

00:53:51.390 --> 00:53:56.400 align:middle line:84%
any Pareto-optimal allocation
has a price p such that x star,

00:53:56.400 --> 00:53:59.130 align:middle line:84%
y star p is a price
quasi-equilibrium

00:53:59.130 --> 00:54:00.060 align:middle line:90%
with transfers.

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:03.900 align:middle line:84%
So it's looking pretty
similar, but we're

00:54:03.900 --> 00:54:05.740 align:middle line:84%
going to prove this
in a different way.

00:54:05.740 --> 00:54:07.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to be
a proof that works

00:54:07.530 --> 00:54:10.860 align:middle line:90%
for quite arbitrary spaces.

00:54:10.860 --> 00:54:12.450 align:middle line:84%
And the proof
that's going to work

00:54:12.450 --> 00:54:14.970 align:middle line:84%
has to do with
separating hyperplanes.

00:54:14.970 --> 00:54:20.100 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind you
what that was about.

00:54:20.100 --> 00:54:22.920 align:middle line:84%
Actually, this is not
quite the right slide.

00:54:22.920 --> 00:54:27.300 align:middle line:84%
This was a review slide about
a supporting hyperplane.

00:54:27.300 --> 00:54:30.270 align:middle line:84%
The better slide was,
we had two convex sets

00:54:30.270 --> 00:54:32.610 align:middle line:90%
that were tangent at a point.

00:54:32.610 --> 00:54:35.640 align:middle line:84%
And then we were able to
draw this hyperplane that

00:54:35.640 --> 00:54:40.200 align:middle line:84%
would be tangent to the common
slope of the two convex sets.

00:54:40.200 --> 00:54:42.270 align:middle line:84%
So all you needed
for the existence

00:54:42.270 --> 00:54:44.940 align:middle line:84%
of supporting and
separating hyperplanes

00:54:44.940 --> 00:54:49.000 align:middle line:84%
is a presumption that
the sets are convex.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:50.380 align:middle line:90%
Here's a picture of it.

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:52.990 align:middle line:84%
We've seen versions
of this before.

00:54:52.990 --> 00:54:56.080 align:middle line:90%
Here's one production set.

00:54:56.080 --> 00:54:58.690 align:middle line:90%
Here's another production set.

00:54:58.690 --> 00:55:03.860 align:middle line:84%
Here's the endowment somewhere
here, I think it was.

00:55:03.860 --> 00:55:07.540 align:middle line:84%
And so we add up the production
sets and the endowments,

00:55:07.540 --> 00:55:11.780 align:middle line:84%
and we get this sort
of outer frontier.

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:16.450 align:middle line:84%
The point being, it's
defining a convex set.

00:55:16.450 --> 00:55:19.800 align:middle line:84%
Things on the frontier
but also interior.

00:55:19.800 --> 00:55:22.230 align:middle line:84%
Any linear combinations
of things in the interior

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:24.740 align:middle line:90%
is also in the interior.

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:27.720 align:middle line:90%
What's this other monster here?

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:30.540 align:middle line:84%
This thing looks like
an indifference curve.

00:55:30.540 --> 00:55:32.660 align:middle line:84%
But, in fact, we have
many, many households.

00:55:32.660 --> 00:55:34.740 align:middle line:90%
So what the heck is it?

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:38.590 align:middle line:90%
Well, it's this thing.

00:55:38.590 --> 00:55:40.630 align:middle line:90%
It's the upper contour set.

00:55:40.630 --> 00:55:46.180 align:middle line:84%
It's the set of allocations,
which are weakly preferred

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:50.050 align:middle line:84%
to the allocation x
star and summed up

00:55:50.050 --> 00:55:53.070 align:middle line:90%
over all the households.

00:55:53.070 --> 00:55:57.680 align:middle line:84%
So that's this thing that looks
like an indifference curve.

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:01.300 align:middle line:84%
But because we have convexity,
this upper contour set

00:56:01.300 --> 00:56:03.100 align:middle line:90%
is also convex.

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:06.160 align:middle line:90%
So now, we have two convex sets.

00:56:06.160 --> 00:56:10.300 align:middle line:84%
We have a supporting
hyperplane for both of them,

00:56:10.300 --> 00:56:13.340 align:middle line:84%
separating supporting
hyperplane.

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:16.290 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
define the price system.

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:18.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is kind
of a graphical way

00:56:18.110 --> 00:56:20.960 align:middle line:84%
to think about that
constructive proof

00:56:20.960 --> 00:56:23.360 align:middle line:84%
without taking
first-order conditions

00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:25.970 align:middle line:84%
and matching up
Lagrange multipliers.

00:56:25.970 --> 00:56:31.190 align:middle line:84%
We're defining using the
convexity and the separating

00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:34.020 align:middle line:84%
supporting hyperplane
theorems to get the prices.

00:56:34.020 --> 00:56:38.120 align:middle line:84%
So in 1954, Debreu
worked all this out.

00:56:38.120 --> 00:56:41.510 align:middle line:84%
He called his equilibrium
a valuation equilibrium,

00:56:41.510 --> 00:56:44.060 align:middle line:84%
as distinct from a
competitive equilibrium.

00:56:44.060 --> 00:56:47.330 align:middle line:84%
Pareto optimality was
defined the same way.

00:56:47.330 --> 00:56:49.410 align:middle line:90%
The environment is similar.

00:56:49.410 --> 00:56:53.420 align:middle line:84%
We have a finite number of
households getting allocations

00:56:53.420 --> 00:56:55.130 align:middle line:90%
in their consumption sets.

00:56:55.130 --> 00:56:59.000 align:middle line:84%
But when it says the consumption
set is a subset of this L,

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:03.570 align:middle line:84%
it does no longer mean a finite
dimensional Euclidean space.

00:57:03.570 --> 00:57:06.440 align:middle line:84%
It's an arbitrary linear
space, conveniently

00:57:06.440 --> 00:57:08.450 align:middle line:90%
denoted L for linear.

00:57:08.450 --> 00:57:10.850 align:middle line:84%
Preferences have a
complete ordering.

00:57:10.850 --> 00:57:12.290 align:middle line:90%
That's rationality.

00:57:12.290 --> 00:57:15.110 align:middle line:84%
Producers J have
a production set,

00:57:15.110 --> 00:57:17.030 align:middle line:90%
choosing objects in the set.

00:57:17.030 --> 00:57:20.360 align:middle line:84%
Also a subset of
the linear space.

00:57:20.360 --> 00:57:22.730 align:middle line:84%
Market clearing
looks pretty similar.

00:57:22.730 --> 00:57:27.140 align:middle line:84%
x equal y plus 6e or
x minus y equals 6e,

00:57:27.140 --> 00:57:29.180 align:middle line:84%
where x is the summation
over households,

00:57:29.180 --> 00:57:31.100 align:middle line:84%
y is the summation
over producers,

00:57:31.100 --> 00:57:33.860 align:middle line:90%
and xi is the endowment.

00:57:33.860 --> 00:57:37.670 align:middle line:84%
So we actually call a state
of the economy something

00:57:37.670 --> 00:57:40.670 align:middle line:84%
that's attainable being in the
production sets, consumption

00:57:40.670 --> 00:57:45.580 align:middle line:84%
sets, and satisfying
the resource constraint.

00:57:45.580 --> 00:57:48.280 align:middle line:90%
So then, we get to the theorems.

00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:50.200 align:middle line:84%
First and second
welfare theorems

00:57:50.200 --> 00:57:53.920 align:middle line:84%
are similar, although the
assumptions are a little bit

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:54.820 align:middle line:90%
different.

00:57:54.820 --> 00:57:57.460 align:middle line:90%
Evaluation equilibrium, i.e.

00:57:57.460 --> 00:58:00.850 align:middle line:84%
competitive equilibrium,
is Pareto optimal.

00:58:00.850 --> 00:58:03.370 align:middle line:84%
What does the price
system look like?

00:58:03.370 --> 00:58:06.070 align:middle line:84%
In these general
linear spaces, it's

00:58:06.070 --> 00:58:09.040 align:middle line:84%
just called a linear
functional, meaning

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:11.470 align:middle line:90%
that it's retaining additivity.

00:58:11.470 --> 00:58:14.260 align:middle line:84%
If you take the valuation
of a weighted average of two

00:58:14.260 --> 00:58:16.000 align:middle line:84%
bundles, it's the
weighted average

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.040 align:middle line:84%
of the valuation
of the two bundles.

00:58:18.040 --> 00:58:19.180 align:middle line:90%
Seems quite natural.

00:58:19.180 --> 00:58:22.330 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, for finite
dimensional Euclidean spaces

00:58:22.330 --> 00:58:26.060 align:middle line:84%
and the dot product,
this holds automatically.

00:58:26.060 --> 00:58:28.790 align:middle line:84%
This is a generalization
of that idea.

00:58:28.790 --> 00:58:34.960 align:middle line:84%
So a valuation equilibrium is
attainable, maximizes utility,

00:58:34.960 --> 00:58:38.260 align:middle line:84%
subject to the budget,
and maximizes profits,

00:58:38.260 --> 00:58:43.660 align:middle line:84%
where the price system is this
valuation function v. This

00:58:43.660 --> 00:58:48.040 align:middle line:84%
is literally utility
maximization because it

00:58:48.040 --> 00:58:52.810 align:middle line:84%
says that if it's in the budget,
it is not preferred to Xi.

00:58:52.810 --> 00:58:55.630 align:middle line:84%
If that weren't true, if you
had a point in the budget that

00:58:55.630 --> 00:59:00.070 align:middle line:84%
were strictly preferred
to the allocation Xi0,

00:59:00.070 --> 00:59:02.020 align:middle line:90%
then it would be chosen.

00:59:02.020 --> 00:59:06.600 align:middle line:84%
So that would contradict
utility maximization.

00:59:06.600 --> 00:59:10.410 align:middle line:84%
The second welfare theorem
of valuation equilibrium

00:59:10.410 --> 00:59:12.990 align:middle line:84%
is a Pareto optimum
welfare theorem.

00:59:12.990 --> 00:59:18.360 align:middle line:84%
What we need, we need convexity
of the consumption sets

00:59:18.360 --> 00:59:22.560 align:middle line:84%
and a little bit more about
convexity of preferences.

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:24.840 align:middle line:90%
We did not need this previously.

00:59:24.840 --> 00:59:27.840 align:middle line:84%
When we had finite
dimensional Euclidean spaces,

00:59:27.840 --> 00:59:30.450 align:middle line:84%
I made a big deal of
saying all we needed

00:59:30.450 --> 00:59:32.640 align:middle line:90%
was local nonsatiation.

00:59:32.640 --> 00:59:35.070 align:middle line:90%
We need no satiation here.

00:59:35.070 --> 00:59:38.940 align:middle line:84%
We also need a little bit more
about convexity of consumption

00:59:38.940 --> 00:59:40.210 align:middle line:90%
sets and preferences.

00:59:40.210 --> 00:59:42.720 align:middle line:84%
So you're trying for
something bigger, something

00:59:42.720 --> 00:59:45.030 align:middle line:84%
that works for a very,
very large number

00:59:45.030 --> 00:59:46.740 align:middle line:84%
of economic
environments, you need

00:59:46.740 --> 00:59:48.220 align:middle line:90%
to assume a little bit more.

00:59:48.220 --> 00:59:51.270 align:middle line:84%
The second welfare
theorem, any Pareto optimum

00:59:51.270 --> 00:59:53.950 align:middle line:84%
can be achieved as a
valuation equilibrium.

00:59:53.950 --> 00:59:57.960 align:middle line:84%
So again, more things
about consumption sets.

00:59:57.960 --> 01:00:02.550 align:middle line:84%
When your combinations of points
in the set are also in the set,

01:00:02.550 --> 01:00:03.660 align:middle line:90%
sets closed.

01:00:03.660 --> 01:00:06.240 align:middle line:84%
Production sets,
when aggregated up,

01:00:06.240 --> 01:00:08.730 align:middle line:84%
the aggregated
production set is convex.

01:00:08.730 --> 01:00:12.930 align:middle line:84%
And here, either L is finite
dimensional or if infinite

01:00:12.930 --> 01:00:16.800 align:middle line:84%
or other dimensional, Y
has an interior point.

01:00:16.800 --> 01:00:19.050 align:middle line:84%
I know this is really,
really abstract.

01:00:19.050 --> 01:00:22.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to show you a couple
of applications momentarily.

01:00:22.500 --> 01:00:25.890 align:middle line:84%
And the theorem is,
assuming the 3, 4,

01:00:25.890 --> 01:00:31.300 align:middle line:84%
and 5, every Pareto-optimal
allocation, which is not

01:00:31.300 --> 01:00:36.040 align:middle line:84%
a satiation point, is associated
with a nontrivial continuous

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:39.280 align:middle line:84%
linear function, where we have
a condition for households

01:00:39.280 --> 01:00:40.780 align:middle line:90%
and a condition for firms.

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:45.820 align:middle line:84%
So here, the condition for
households is that if Xi,

01:00:45.820 --> 01:00:49.360 align:middle line:84%
we have the Pareto optimal
allocation Pareto Xi0.

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:52.030 align:middle line:84%
We have an allocation that
is strictly weakly preferred

01:00:52.030 --> 01:00:55.790 align:middle line:84%
to Xi0 and is in
the consumption set,

01:00:55.790 --> 01:01:00.160 align:middle line:84%
then this implies the valuation
of that other allocation Xi

01:01:00.160 --> 01:01:03.430 align:middle line:84%
is not less than the
valuation of Xi0.

01:01:03.430 --> 01:01:06.670 align:middle line:84%
This corresponds to
cost minimization.

01:01:06.670 --> 01:01:08.620 align:middle line:90%
And again, just reverse it.

01:01:08.620 --> 01:01:12.790 align:middle line:84%
If the valuation were
less than Xi0, then

01:01:12.790 --> 01:01:16.750 align:middle line:84%
that other point is, say,
better, maybe indifferent.

01:01:16.750 --> 01:01:20.380 align:middle line:84%
But because we have
local nonsatiation, just

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:23.200 align:middle line:84%
like the Lemma, we could
construct something close

01:01:23.200 --> 01:01:27.520 align:middle line:84%
by which is strictly better
and in the budget set for Xi0.

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:29.050 align:middle line:84%
So that would be
a contradiction.

01:01:29.050 --> 01:01:31.720 align:middle line:84%
So this is the cost
minimization part.

01:01:31.720 --> 01:01:37.000 align:middle line:84%
This is why it's going to
be a quasi-equilibrium, not

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.190 align:middle line:90%
a full equilibrium.

01:01:39.190 --> 01:01:41.680 align:middle line:84%
So I feel like it
took a lot of work

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:43.660 align:middle line:90%
to get through all of this.

01:01:43.660 --> 01:01:45.970 align:middle line:84%
The main takeaways
are, there's a way

01:01:45.970 --> 01:01:49.090 align:middle line:84%
to do things more generally
with separating and supporting

01:01:49.090 --> 01:01:52.990 align:middle line:84%
hyperplanes, as long as we
have sufficient convexity.

01:01:52.990 --> 01:01:55.990 align:middle line:84%
I took the time to take you
through Debreu's article.

01:01:55.990 --> 01:01:59.500 align:middle line:84%
It's really very similar,
apart from changes in notation,

01:01:59.500 --> 01:02:03.250 align:middle line:84%
to what we did with the finite
dimensional Euclidean spaces.

01:02:03.250 --> 01:02:08.260 align:middle line:84%
But it applies to
other economies,

01:02:08.260 --> 01:02:10.480 align:middle line:84%
in particular,
competitive equilibria

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:13.450 align:middle line:84%
in the space of
contracts, including

01:02:13.450 --> 01:02:16.030 align:middle line:84%
the possibility of
randomized allocations

01:02:16.030 --> 01:02:18.690 align:middle line:90%
that we've used before.

01:02:18.690 --> 01:02:22.700 align:middle line:84%
So I think I mentioned
contracts with options,

01:02:22.700 --> 01:02:25.520 align:middle line:84%
like CDs where you
could withdraw early

01:02:25.520 --> 01:02:29.150 align:middle line:84%
or pensions where you could
decide to take a lump sum

01:02:29.150 --> 01:02:31.130 align:middle line:90%
or take an annuity.

01:02:31.130 --> 01:02:35.150 align:middle line:84%
I gave you those as examples
of contracts with options.

01:02:35.150 --> 01:02:36.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we had a
couple of lectures

01:02:36.650 --> 01:02:38.330 align:middle line:90%
talking about contracts.

01:02:38.330 --> 01:02:41.600 align:middle line:84%
I'm sparing you
